WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:04.720
<v Speaker 1>What was the word for problem in Spanish?

00:00:04.720 --> 00:00:05.840
<v Speaker 2>Problema.

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:06.560
<v Speaker 1>Problema.

00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:08.080
<v Speaker 1>And the problem?

00:00:09.040 --> 00:00:10.160
<v Speaker 2>El problema.

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:11.679
<v Speaker 1>El problema, good.

00:00:11.679 --> 00:00:21.279
<v Speaker 1>We can see it ends in an A, so we would expect it to be feminine, but we saw that these words ending MA in Spanish

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:32.300
<v Speaker 1>Many of them entered through Greek and in Greek they're neuter but they look a bit masculine in Greek so they came into Spanish as masculine words even though they end in A.

00:00:32.300 --> 00:00:35.020
<v Speaker 1>So we have el problema system

00:00:36.740 --> 00:00:37.620
<v Speaker 1>Sistema.

00:00:37.620 --> 00:00:40.420
<v Speaker 1>Sistema the system.

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:41.540
<v Speaker 2>El sistema.

00:00:41.540 --> 00:00:42.340
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:42.340 --> 00:00:44.020
<v Speaker 1>The paradigm.

00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:46.500
<v Speaker 1>How do you think that would be in Spanish?

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:48.840
<v Speaker 2>El paradigma.

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:50.920
<v Speaker 1>El paradigma, good.

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:53.800
<v Speaker 1>Scheme also came in from Greek.

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:57.719
<v Speaker 1>But scheme in Spanish means outline or diagram.

00:00:57.719 --> 00:00:59.640
<v Speaker 1>How do you think that would be?

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:01.879
<v Speaker 1>El esquema.

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:03.399
<v Speaker 1>El esquema.

00:01:03.399 --> 00:01:03.879
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:03.879 --> 00:01:07.080
<v Speaker 1>And something else to make it sound a bit more Spanish?

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:08.840
<v Speaker 1>El esquema.

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:09.400
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:10.520
<v Speaker 1>El esquema.

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:12.200
<v Speaker 1>We said that we cannot start s

00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:14.860
<v Speaker 1>plus another consonant in Spanish.

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:20.700
<v Speaker 1>We have to put an E before, like Spain, Espana, Spaghetti, Espagueti, El Esquema.

00:01:20.700 --> 00:01:22.380
<v Speaker 1>So this would be outline or diagram.

00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:24.220
<v Speaker 1>Diagram is another one of these words.

00:01:24.220 --> 00:01:26.620
<v Speaker 1>How do you think that would be in Spanish?

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:28.240
<v Speaker 2>Diagramma.

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:28.560
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:30.240
<v Speaker 1>And the diagram?

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:31.600
<v Speaker 2>El Diagramma.

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:33.040
<v Speaker 1>El Diagramma.

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:33.840
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:34.160
<v Speaker 1>So

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:42.320
<v Speaker 1>Mostly words ending O are masculine and words ending a are feminine, but we might find some exceptions.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:44.080
<v Speaker 1>Planeta, for example.

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:45.280
<v Speaker 1>What do you think that means?

00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:46.080
<v Speaker 1>Planeta

00:01:46.439 --> 00:01:47.399
<v Speaker 2>Planet.

00:01:47.399 --> 00:01:49.640
<v Speaker 1>Planeta is a masculine word.

00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:51.719
<v Speaker 1>So the planet.

00:01:51.719 --> 00:01:52.920
<v Speaker 2>El planeta.

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:53.960
<v Speaker 1>El planeta.

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:56.039
<v Speaker 1>A planet.

00:01:56.600 --> 00:01:57.880
<v Speaker 2>Un planeta.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:01:59.320
<v Speaker 1>Un planeta, very good.

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:02.600
<v Speaker 1>How would you say the planets?

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:04.360
<v Speaker 2>Los planetas.

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:05.000
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:06.600
<v Speaker 1>Los planetas.

00:02:06.600 --> 00:02:07.160
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:10.680
<v Speaker 1>So this is a masculine word that looks feminine.

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:11.800
<v Speaker 1>How was the word for car?

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:14.360
<v Speaker 1>We saw various words.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:15.160
<v Speaker 2>Auto?

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:15.720
<v Speaker 1>Auto.

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:17.319
<v Speaker 1>Let's work with that one.

00:02:17.319 --> 00:02:20.040
<v Speaker 1>How do you say the car?

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:21.160
<v Speaker 2>El auto.

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:22.280
<v Speaker 1>The cars

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:24.900
<v Speaker 2>Los autos.

00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:26.500
<v Speaker 1>Los autos, good.

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:31.860
<v Speaker 1>If you want to say this car, you say este auto.

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:33.460
<v Speaker 1>Este auto.

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:34.820
<v Speaker 2>Este auto.

00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:35.380
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:38.500
<v Speaker 1>We saw esta noche this night.

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:42.500
<v Speaker 1>What do you think is the difference between este and esta then?

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:48.480
<v Speaker 1>If we have este auto and esta noche, what do you think is the difference?

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:50.720
<v Speaker 2>Este is the masculine.

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:51.120
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:52.560
<v Speaker 2>And esta the feminine.

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:52.960
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:55.600
<v Speaker 1>So we see that noce is a feminine word.

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:56.960
<v Speaker 1>How would you say the night?

00:02:58.560 --> 00:02:59.520
<v Speaker 2>La noche.

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:00.480
<v Speaker 1>La noche.

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:02.640
<v Speaker 1>The nights.

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:04.080
<v Speaker 2>Las noches.

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:04.560
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:06.560
<v Speaker 1>But this night or tonight

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:08.560
<v Speaker 2>Esta noche.

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:09.840
<v Speaker 1>Esta noche.

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:10.480
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:10.480 --> 00:03:19.280
<v Speaker 1>If you take this T out of este and esta, the words for this, you get the word for that.

00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:27.440
<v Speaker 1>So este auto is this car and that car would be auto.

00:03:28.319 --> 00:03:30.800
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I want that car?

00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:33.340
<v Speaker 2>Quiero ese auto.

00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:33.819
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:33.819 --> 00:03:37.660
<v Speaker 1>I don't want that car because it's very big.

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:39.500
<v Speaker 1>Big is a grand.

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:41.819
<v Speaker 1>So how would that be in Spanish?

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:55.520
<v Speaker 1>Very good

00:03:55.980 --> 00:04:00.540
<v Speaker 1>No quiero ese auto because it's muy grande.

00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:02.460
<v Speaker 1>How was this night?

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:06.700
<v Speaker 1>And how would be that night?

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:08.280
<v Speaker 2>Esa noche.

00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:09.160
<v Speaker 1>Esa noche.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:11.880
<v Speaker 1>We just get rid of the T and then we have the word for that.

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:15.000
<v Speaker 1>What if you wanted to say those nights?

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:17.720
<v Speaker 1>Esas noches.

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:19.480
<v Speaker 1>Essas noches.

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:20.440
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:25.000
<v Speaker 1>There are also a few words that end in o which are feminine.

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:31.120
<v Speaker 1>For example, mano mano means hand ends in oh but it's a feminine word.

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:34.479
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say the hand?

00:04:34.479 --> 00:04:37.680
<v Speaker 1>La mano La mano good the hands

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:40.960
<v Speaker 2>Las manos.

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:42.240
<v Speaker 1>Las manos.

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:46.000
<v Speaker 2>This hand esta mano.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:46.479
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:46.479 --> 00:04:47.280
<v Speaker 1>That hand

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:50.060
<v Speaker 2>Essa mano.

00:04:50.060 --> 00:04:50.540
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:53.180
<v Speaker 1>These hands.

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:54.780
<v Speaker 2>Estas manos.

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:55.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:55.580 --> 00:04:59.500
<v Speaker 1>We have this word in English like in manuscript.

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:03.800
<v Speaker 1>Manual as well, manual, manuscript, that that man bit there means hand.

00:05:03.800 --> 00:05:07.480
<v Speaker 1>Maintain, which in Spanish is a maner.

00:05:07.480 --> 00:05:10.760
<v Speaker 1>We have main or man means hand.

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:14.280
<v Speaker 1>Manage, manage means to handle.

00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:19.400
<v Speaker 1>Actually, it has a special use for handling horses.

00:05:19.220 --> 00:05:27.139
<v Speaker 1>historically, which is interesting because to manage manejar is used in some Latin American countries to mean to drive.

00:05:27.139 --> 00:05:29.860
<v Speaker 1>Other than to manage or to handle, it also means

00:05:29.940 --> 00:05:42.420
<v Speaker 1>to drive manekhar, which is interesting because this verb manage historically had a special use to handle horses and we see how that's kind of translated over the years to driving.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:47.080
<v Speaker 1>How would you say, can you give me a hand?

